> (204 forbids a body)</td></tr>
    </tbody></table>
    </div>

    <details>
      <summary>Database layer <span class=3D"badge">db/index.ts + models/ta=
sk.model.ts</span></summary>
      <div class=3D"details-body">
        <p>One table, created with <code>CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS</code> =
on every boot (no migration tool =E2=80=94 fine here, wouldn't scale to sch=
ema changes over time in a real app).</p>
        <pre>CREATE TABLE tasks (
  id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
  title TEXT NOT NULL,
  priority TEXT NOT NULL CHECK (priority IN ('low','medium','high')),
  is_complete BOOLEAN NOT NULL DEFAULT FALSE CHECK (is_complete IN (FALSE, =
TRUE)),
  created_at TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT (datetime('now'))
)</pre>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>WAL mode</strong> (<code>journal_mode =3D WAL</code>)=
 =E2=80=94 better read concurrency, standard choice for SQLite web apps.</l=
i>
          <li><strong>CHECK constraints</strong> on <code>priority</code> a=
nd <code>is_complete</code> back up app-level validation at the schema leve=
l =E2=80=94 defense in depth.</li>
          <li>All four queries are <strong>prepared statements</strong> com=
piled once at module load (<code>db.prepare(...)</code> at the top level), =
not per-request =E2=80=94 faster, and immune to SQL injection since values =
are always bound params, never string-concatenated.</li>
          <li><strong>INSERT/UPDATE both use <code>RETURNING</code></strong=
> =E2=80=94 the fresh row comes back from the same round trip, no follow-up=
 <code>SELECT</code>.</li>
          <li><strong>Partial update via <code>COALESCE</code></strong>: <c=
ode>title =3D COALESCE(@title, title)</code> etc. =E2=80=94 pass <code>null=
</code> for a field you don't want to touch, the row keeps its old value. T=
his is what makes <code>PATCH</code> semantics work without reading the row=
 first.</li>
          <li><strong>Boolean handling</strong>: SQLite has no real boolean=
 type and better-sqlite3 will only bind numbers/strings/bigints/buffers/nul=
l =E2=80=94 never a raw JS boolean. <code>toDbBool()</code> converts <code>=
true/false/undefined</code> =E2=86=92 <code>1/0/null</code> before every wr=
ite; <code>rowToTask()</code> converts <code>is_complete =3D=3D=3D 1</code>=
 back to a boolean on every read. Two distinct types exist for this reason:=
 <code>TaskRow</code> (raw DB shape: snake_case, 0/1) vs <code>Task</code> =
(API shape: camelCase, real boolean) =E2=80=94 the DB shape never leaks pas=
t <code>task.model.ts</code>.</li>
          <li><code>deleteTask</code> returns <code>changes &gt; 0</code> a=
s a boolean =E2=80=94 that's how the controller knows to 404 vs 200.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details open=3D"">
      <summary>Validation <span class=3D"badge">validators/task.validator.t=
s</span></summary>
      <div class=3D"details-body">
        <p>Hand-rolled, no schema library (no zod/joi/yup). Three functions=
: <code>parseId</code>, <code>parseCreate</code>, <code>parseUpdate</code> =
=E2=80=94 each takes an <code>unknown</code> and either returns a typed, tr=
immed value or throws <code>AppError(400, ...)</code>.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><code>parseId</code> =E2=80=94 guards against Express's <code=
>req.params.id</code> technically being a <code>string[]</code>, then check=
s it's a positive integer.</li>
          <li><code>parseCreate</code> =E2=80=94 <code>title</code> must be=
 a non-empty string after trim; <code>priority</code> must be one of the th=
ree literals (via an <code>isPriority</code> type guard reused from <code>u=
tils/task.ts</code>); <code>isComplete</code> optional but must be boolean =
if present.</li>
          <li><code>parseUpdate</code> =E2=80=94 same field checks, but req=
uires <em>at least one</em> field present (otherwise a 400) =E2=80=94 this =
is what makes <code>PATCH</code> meaningfully different from <code>PUT</cod=
e>: a partial, non-empty patch.</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Why not zod here:</strong> reasonable default answer =E2=
=80=94 small surface area (3 fields, 2 endpoints that accept a body), kept =
dependencies minimal. Fair thing to volunteer as a "next step": a shared zo=
d schema could generate both the server validator and a client-side type, r=
emoving the current manual duplication between server validators and client=
 types.</p>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>Error handling <span class=3D"badge">errors/app-error.ts + m=
iddleware/catch-errors.ts + middleware/error-handler.ts</span></summary>
      <div class=3D"details-body">
        <ul>
          <li><code>AppError</code> =E2=80=94 a plain <code>Error</code> su=
bclass carrying a <code>statusCode</code>. Thrown anywhere in a handler/val=
idator/controller to fail a request with a specific status.</li>
          <li><code>catchErrors(handler)</code> =E2=80=94 wraps every contr=
oller. Calls the handler, wraps it in <code>Promise.resolve(...).catch(next=
)</code> <em>and</em> has a synchronous <code>try/catch</code> around the c=
all itself. Reason stated in the comment: a plain try/catch alone won't cat=
ch a rejected promise, so this stays correct even if a handler becomes <cod=
e>async</code> later without anyone remembering to add error handling.</li>
          <li><code>errorHandler</code> (the last app-level middleware) =E2=
=80=94 three cases: <code>AppError</code> =E2=86=92 its own status + messag=
e; a body-parser error (malformed JSON, payload too large =E2=80=94 these c=
ome in as plain <code>Error</code>s with a numeric <code>status</code>/<cod=
e>statusCode</code> in the 4xx range) =E2=86=92 forwarded as that status in=
stead of collapsing to a generic 500; anything else =E2=86=92 logged server=
-side, generic 500 returned to the client (no internals leaked).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>Rate limiting <span class=3D"badge">middleware/rate-limit.ts=
</span></summary>
      <div class=3D"details-body">
        <p>Two limiters stacked on <code>/api/tasks</code>, both from <code=
>express-rate-limit</code>, both in-memory (per-process, resets on restart,=
 wouldn't coordinate across multiple server instances):</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Burst</strong> =E2=80=94 5 requests / 2 seconds. Stop=
s rapid click-spam (e.g. mashing delete or the done/todo checkbox).</li>
          <li><strong>Sustained</strong> =E2=80=94 30 requests / 60 seconds=
. General abuse guard; comment notes 30/min sits at the low end of typical =
write-API limits, justified since every endpoint here does a DB write or a =
full-table read.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>

    <details open=3D"">
      <summary>What changed from the starter code</summary>
      <div class=3D"details-body">
        <p>The starter (still visible in git history, commit <code>e77b869<=
/code>/<code>213526f</code>) had: a DB connection + <code>CREATE TABLE</cod=
e>, one <code>TaskModel</code> object (<code>findAll/findById/create/update=
/delete</code>) inlined into a single <code>GET /api/tasks</code> route dir=
ectly in <code>index.ts</code>, and a placeholder React component. No valid=
ation, no error handling, no rate limiting, no other verbs, and the schema =
